\intbl \ql \b Background\b0 \line The Auckland Park Theological Seminary is a Private Higher Education Institution registered with the Department of Higher Education and Training and also has programmes accredited by the CHE.\line \line The Institution applied for the accreditation of a Bachelor Honours of Theology which was tabled at the AC meeting held on the 8th of May 2018 and the HEQC meeting held on the 30th of August 2018.\line \line The programme was not accredited for the following reasons\'3A\line 1. The Institution has not provided a properly conceived\'2C coherently described\line and planned strategy for the delivery of this programme in the distance learning\line mode. The full programme design \'28including modular components\'2C compulsory\line and elective modules and rules of combination\'2C and in particular also the\line research components regarding credits values and HEQSF-level\'29 demonstrate a\line lack of understanding of the role\'2C function and quality issues associated with\line learning materials in the distance mode of provision. \line 2. Programme design has critical weaknesses in terms of the following\'3A\line - There is a lack of coherence and the design of the programme is ill-conceived.\line - Programme design is not anchored in a clearly defined and integrated\line understanding of distance education.\line - Rules of combination are unclear and contribute to the lack of programme\line coherence and purposefulness. Modules appear to be ad hoc with little\line explanation for the particular selection.\line - Module outlines are vague and while an attempt is made to allow the NQF\line level descriptors to inform outcomes\'2C ATS have just simply adopted the\line descriptors as outcomes. No actual module outlines are presented.\line - The reading list provided is dated and lacks contextualisation.\line - It is unclear whether all the modules in the Honours programme are\line appropriate for NQF level 8 including the Research Methodology module \'288\line credits\'29 which is not designed for NQF level 8 learning.\line 3. Module names and codes in the application and the SAQA submission are\line not aligned.\line 4. The Institution has not demonstrated its understanding of RPL\'2FCAT and\line Articulation and its policy statements are not in line with the relevant\line legislative frameworks. \line 5. The Institution has not clarified what happens to prospective students who do\line not successfully complete the English proficiency test\'2C and their continuing\line involvement in ATS programmes. The admission requirements should at least\line provide some explanation for the additional requirement of 60\'25 average given\line the proposed audience in the context of widening access. \line 6. A lack of clarity exists on the availability of academic and support staff\line members allocated to the programme\'2C their suitability as well as their\line involvement on this as well as other programmes envisaged or already offered\line at the Institution. The Institution has also not submitted a Workload Allocation\line Model indicating the duties and responsibilities of staff members in the\line implementation of the programme.\line 7. The Assessment and Moderation Policy is not in line with the requirements\line for accreditation of a programme for the distance mode.\line 8. The Institution\'27s Library Policy is inadequate on how distance students are\line supported in an equitable manner and detail of plans to make provision for\line students in the distance mode through the Library is lacking.\line 9. The Institution has not provided clear and unambiguous evidence that the\line programme was designed with the distance education mode supported by the\line design and focus in the Teaching and Learning Policy and related mechanisms.\line The Institution\'27s research policy does not include an emphasis on research on\line DE and the Institution\'27s systems for monitoring students is not adequate.\line \line The Institution has submitted a representation.\cell \pard 

